I have put a lot more strict rules in place ... these will prevent us from having diverging versions again and will inform us if there are CVEs reported for dependencies we use. 

In general the rule is: don't define the versions of plugins and third-party dependencies locally, if you add a new third party dependency or plugin, add that to the pluginManagement or dependencyManagement of the main pom and then use notation without version in sub-modules.

Another rule is, that if you use something in your code, you need to add a dependency to that artifact in the correct scope, otherwise the build will fail. The reasoning behind this is, that if you rely on transitive dependencies, these possibly change without us noticing causing hard to debug problems.

On the first look it does seem as if this process adds a bit more work for the developer, which it does. However long-term it pays off 10 time as managing dependency problems becomes really easy and it has saved us many days of tracing down tricky problems. 

For example in the current "Master" branch we use different versions of ratis ... unfortunately versions that are API incompatible.
